response:
I have a complete picture. Here is the full diagnosis, root cause, fix, and principle.

---

## Diagnosis

The bug has **two interacting layers**. The comment thread in the code ("See FB-156") shows a *previous* attempted fix that addressed the wrong anchor element. The real cause was never the anchor element — it is a **coordinate-space mismatch** between what the CSS transform on `.highlightLabelAnchor` expects and what `getBoundingClientRect()` delivers.

### Layer 1 — The CSS contract (what should happen)

`.highlightLabelAnchor` is `position: fixed` and carries:

```scss
transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
```

This transform is designed to:
- pull the element **100% of its own width** to the left, **plus** the gutter spacer (`$portfolio-spacing-03`), so its right edge lands exactly at the gutter line
- vertically centre it on its anchor point (`-50%`)

The intent is identical to how the in-rail `.label` works:

```scss
// in-rail hover label
right: calc(100% + #{$portfolio-spacing-03});
```

Both formulas place the label's right edge at `notch.left – $portfolio-spacing-03`. ✅ *The CSS formula itself is correct.*

### Layer 2 — The coordinate fed into `style.left` (what actually happens)

In `useIsomorphicLayoutEffect`, the compute function does:

```ts
const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
setOverlayPos({
  top: r.top + r.height / 2,   // vertical centre of the notch ✅
  left: r.left,                 // ← THE BUG
});
```

`r.left` is the **left edge of the `.notch` container**. The `.notch` is `width: 28px` and is `justify-content: flex-end` inside a right-aligned flex track. The tick button (16 px–28 px wide) lives inside it, also right-aligned. The **right edge of the notch** is what everything should hinge on — it is the gutter line that all in-rail labels are `right: calc(100% + spacer)` from.

By passing `r.left` to `style.left`, the anchor is placed at the notch's *left* edge, not its *right* edge. The CSS transform then pulls the label further left from an already-too-left starting point, sliding the label **entirely off-screen to the left**. When the transform is wrong in the other direction (or stripped), the label shoots out to the **right** past the viewport edge, which matches the symptom exactly.

The previous attempted fix — changing the anchor from the inner tick to the notch container — moved the query selector but kept `r.left`, so there was no visible change: the notch and the tick share the same right edge relative to the rail, and the offset was the same.

**Root cause (AP-072 — Viewport-coordinate anchor mismatch):** `style.left` is fed `r.left` (the notch's left edge in viewport coordinates) but the CSS transform `translate(-100% - spacer, -50%)` expects `style.left` to be the **right edge** of the notch in viewport coordinates (`r.right`). The label is displaced left by exactly `notch.width` (28 px) relative to where every in-rail label sits, landing it either off-screen left (with the transform) or off-screen right (without).

---

## Fix

Two files change. The logic fix is one character in the TS; the SCSS gains a defensive comment so the contract is explicit.

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.tsx`

```diff
       const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
       setOverlayPos({
         top: r.top + r.height / 2,
-        left: r.left,
+        left: r.right,           // right edge = the gutter line; CSS transform
+                                 // translate(-100%-spacer, -50%) pulls the
+                                 // label left from this point, matching the
+                                 // in-rail `right: calc(100% + spacer)` rule.
       });
```

Full updated `compute` block for clarity:

```ts
const compute = () => {
  const notch = trackRef.current?.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
    `[data-notch-index="${highlightIndex}"]`,
  );
  if (!notch) {
    setOverlayPos(null);
    return;
  }
  const r = notch.getBoundingClientRect();
  setOverlayPos({
    top: r.top + r.height / 2,
    // ✅ r.right = notch's right edge in viewport coords.
    // .highlightLabelAnchor uses translate(-100% - $spacing-03, -50%),
    // which mirrors exactly what .label does with
    // `right: calc(100% + $spacing-03)` relative to the notch.
    // Feeding r.left here displaced the label by –notch.width (28 px),
    // sending it off-screen. AP-072.
    left: r.right,
  });
};
```

### `src/components/ScrollSpy.module.scss`

Add a contract comment directly on `.highlightLabelAnchor` so the coupling is documented in the CSS, not just the TS:

```diff
 .highlightLabelAnchor {
   position: fixed;
+  // `left` is set in JS to notch.getBoundingClientRect().right — the notch's
+  // RIGHT edge in viewport coords, which is the shared gutter line.
+  // translate(-100% - spacing-03) then pulls the label left from that point,
+  // reproducing the in-rail `right: calc(100% + spacing-03)` rule exactly.
+  // If you change the JS anchor, update this comment. (AP-072)
   transform: translate(calc(-100% - #{$portfolio-spacing-03}), -50%);
   color: #fff;
   mix-blend-mode: difference;
   z-index: 41;
   pointer-events: none;
   will-change: top, left;
 }
```

---

## Why the previous fix had no effect

The attempted fix changed:

```ts
// before: inner tick button
const tick = trackRef.current?.querySelector<HTMLElement>(`[data-notch-index="${highlightIndex}"] .${styles.tick}`);

// after: notch container
const notch = trackRef.current?.querySelector<HTMLElement>(`[data-notch-index="${highlightIndex}"]`);
```

But in both cases the code took `.left` off the resulting rect. Because `.notch` is `justify-content: flex-end` and `.tick` is right-aligned inside it, the **right edges of the tick and the notch are identical** — both sit flush against the rail's right boundary. The *left* edges differ (tick is narrower), but since the code always used `.left`, the portaled label was off by `notch.width` in one case and `tick.width` in the other — both wrong, and the visual difference was only ~6–12 px, easily dismissed as "no visible change."

---

## Principle

> **AP-072 — Portaled element viewport-coordinate contract:** When a CSS `transform` on a portaled/fixed element is used as the placement mechanism, the JS coordinate fed into `style.top/left` must match the *geometric reference point the transform is written against*. Here: `translate(-100%, …)` pulls left from `style.left`, so `style.left` must be the **right** edge of the anchor element. Any rename of the DOM query must also audit which edge (`.left` vs `.right` vs `.left + width/2`) the transform expects. Document this coupling with an inline comment on both the SCSS rule and the JS `setOverlayPos` call.
